"1988 Massacre: Today's Commemoration of Victims to Prevent Current Evils in Belarus" is the motto of the events marking the 20th anniversary of the events of 1988 in the Belarusian language and handed down from the official letter of the Amnesty International Europe and Baltic States Program. (www.amnesty.org) We invite everyone to take part in the commemoration.

In 1988, as in any regained freedom, the people of Belarus blindly sought out truth,' the road to human rights and democracy, liberty, independence. Belarusian society is in constant and acute need of liberating the truth, liberating people from unnecessary burdens and unreasonable fears, from deliberate obstacles and false values. It is obvious that the events of 1988 never address the problems of the present days. The speech of the Chairman of the Short-term Commission, Mr. Aleksei Flaagan, made it clear: it was not a political court and the only participants were the accused and the judges. This investigation was quite accurate as far as it was concerned. "Belarus is a constituent part of the United Nations and possesses sovereign rights on human rights" (article 9).
